== Overview == In February {{ill|1822|ja|文政5th year|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1822|qq=}}, Seishiro Mitoma accidentally discovered the site while excavating soil from a field at Minamishouji for building walls<ref>{{Cite book|author=Itoshima District Social Education Promotion Council|title=Ito Kingdom Archaeological Guidebook|publisher=Itoshima Newspaper|date=2001-4-30|page=52}}</ref>. In {{ill|1974|ja|昭和49th year|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1974|qq=}}, a re-excavation revealed the "second jar burial." Academic investigations during the Heisei period confirmed the presence of a surrounding moat, identifying the site as a "square-moat Kofun" containing two jar burials. The jars are classified as "Tateiwa-style early-phase" from the middle Yayoi period. Ritual traces have been observed in the western moat, with potential links to the {{ill|Takazusayama mountain range|ja|高祖山|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takazusayama mountain range|qq=}} to the east. These characteristics anticipate the features seen in the later {{ill|Hirabaru Ruins|ja|平原遺跡|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hirabaru Site|qq=}} Kofun 1<ref>"Mikumo Site: Minamishouji District," Fukuoka Prefectural Cultural Property Survey Report No. 69, Fukuoka Prefectural Board of Education, 1985.</ref>.
Recent studies suggest that the Mikumo Minamishouji Site and the [[:en:Suguokamoto_Site|Suguokamoto Site]] burial with a large jar beneath a megalith in Kasuga City may have similar structural scales<ref>"History of Fukuoka from Nature and Archaeology," Fukuoka City Historical Compilation Committee, 2013.</ref>.
