[[sn:Mikumo Nanokoji Site]] [[ja:三雲南小路遺跡]] [[sn:ikumo Nanokoji Site]] [[en:Mikumo Nanokoji Site]]
<!--Mikumo Nanokoji Site--><!--Mikumo Nanokoji Site--><!--Mikumo Nanokoji Site--><!--Mikumo Nanokoji Site--><!--Mikumo Nanokoji Site--><!--Mikumo Nanokoji Site-->

[[File:Mikumo-Minamishouji Site, zenkei.jpg|250px|right|thumb|Mikumo Minamishouji Site ({{ill|Mikumo-Ihara Site|ja|三雲・井原遺跡|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mikumo-Ihara Site|qq=}} Minamishouji District).]] {{Coord|33|32|12.1|N|130|14|29.6|E|display=title}} {{Location map|Japan Fukuoka Prefecture|relief=1| lat_deg = 33| lat_min = 32| lat_sec = 12.1| lon_deg = 130| lon_min = 14| lon_sec = 29.6| label = Mikumo Minamishouji Site| position = bottom| mark = Red pog.svg| marksize = 10| width = 250| caption = {{Center|Location}}| float =right}} '''Mikumo Minamishouji Site''' (三雲南小路遺跡) is a {{ill|Yayoi period|ja|弥生時代|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yayoi period|qq=}} archaeological site located in Mikumo, {{ill|Itoshima, Fukuoka|ja|糸島市|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Itoshima, Fukuoka|qq=}}, Fukuoka Prefecture. It is part of the [[:en:Mikumo-Iwara_Site|Mikumo-Iwara Site]], which has been designated as a {{ill|National Historic Site of Japan|ja|国の史跡|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/National Historic Site of Japan|qq=}}<ref>[http://www.city.itoshima.lg.jp/s033/010/020/010/050/030/bunkazai3.html "List of Historic Sites" (Itoshima City Website)]</ref>. The site is located behind {{ill|Saisa Shrine|ja|細石神社|1=Sazareishi Shrine|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Saisa Shrine|qq=}} and includes a square Kofun (30 meters on each side) with two jar burials and a surrounding moat. It is considered a royal tomb of the ancient {{ill|Itokoku|lt=Ito Kingdom|ja|伊都国|1=Itokoku|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Itokoku|13=User:Immanuelle/Itokoku|qq=}}<ref name=Itoshima>{{Cite web|author=Department of Regional Promotion, Cultural Division|url=https://www.city.itoshima.lg.jp/s033/010/020/010/170/20171129102855.html|title=The Royal Capital of Ito Kingdom: "Mikumo-Ihara Site" Designated as a National Historic Site|work=Itoshima City|accessdate=2022-11-19}}</ref>.
== Overview == In February {{ill|1822|ja|文政5th year|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1822|qq=}}, Seishiro Mitoma accidentally discovered the site while excavating soil from a field at Minamishouji for building walls<ref>{{Cite book|author=Itoshima District Social Education Promotion Council|title=Ito Kingdom Archaeological Guidebook|publisher=Itoshima Newspaper|date=2001-4-30|page=52}}</ref>. In {{ill|1974|ja|昭和49th year|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1974|qq=}}, a re-excavation revealed the "second jar burial." Academic investigations during the Heisei period confirmed the presence of a surrounding moat, identifying the site as a "square-moat Kofun" containing two jar burials. The jars are classified as "Tateiwa-style early-phase" from the middle Yayoi period. Ritual traces have been observed in the western moat, with potential links to the {{ill|Mount Takasu|lt=Mount Takasu|lt=Takazusayama mountain range|ja|高祖山|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takazusayama mountain range|qq=}} to the east. These characteristics anticipate the features seen in the later {{ill|Hirabaru Ruins|ja|平原遺跡|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hirabaru Site|qq=}} Kofun 1<ref>"Mikumo Site: Minamishouji District," Fukuoka Prefectural Cultural Property Survey Report No. 69, Fukuoka Prefectural Board of Education, 1985.</ref>.
Recent studies suggest that the Mikumo Minamishouji Site and the [[:en:Suguokamoto_Site|Suguokamoto Site]] burial with a large jar beneath a megalith in Kasuga City may have similar structural scales<ref>"History of Fukuoka from Nature and Archaeology," Fukuoka City Historical Compilation Committee, 2013.</ref>.
== Grave Goods<ref>"Rikuen Old Artifacts Analysis" by Munetada Aoyagi, "Mikumo Site: Minamishouji District," Fukuoka Prefectural Cultural Property Survey Report No. 69, Fukuoka Prefectural Board of Education, 1985.</ref> == '''Jar Burial 1''' * '''Outside the jar''' ** 1 bronze sword ** 1 bronze halberd ** 1 small vermilion-stained jar * '''Inside the jar''' ** 2 bronze spears ** 31 or more bronze mirrors ({{ill|Han-style mirror|lt=Han-style mirror|lt=Han mirrors|ja|前漢鏡|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Han mirrors|qq=}}) ** 8 or more fragments of glass bi disks (lapis lazuli) ** 3 glass magatama beads ** Over 60 glass tubular beads ** 8 or more gold-co11er four-leaf decorative fittings ** '''Bronze mirrors''': Sizes range from 27.3 cm to 16.0 cm. Most are {{ill|Inscribed mirror|lt=Linked arc-patterned inscribed band mirrors|ja|異体字銘帯鏡|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Inscribed mirror|qq=}}, comprising 26 or more specimens.
'''Jar Burial 2''' * 22 or more bronze mirrors (Han mirrors) * 1 glass pendant (possibly reused fragments of a lapis lazuli bi disk) * 13 magatama beads (1 jadeite, 12 glass) * '''Bronze mirrors''': Sizes range from 11.4 cm to 6.0 cm. Most are {{ill|Inscribed mirror|lt=Linked arc-patterned "Sunlight" inscribed mirrors|ja|連弧文「日光」銘鏡|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Inscribed mirror|qq=}}, comprising 16 or more specimens.
== Notes ==
{{Reflist}}
== References == * "Rikuen Old Artifacts Analysis" by Munetada Aoyagi * "The Tragedy of the Golden Seal" by Dairoku Harada * "Mikumo Site: Minamishouji District," Fukuoka Prefectural Cultural Property Survey Report No. 69, Fukuoka Prefectural Board of Education, 1985 * "History of Fukuoka from Nature and Archaeology," Fukuoka City Historical Compilation Committee, 2013 == See Also == * {{ill|Itokoku|ja|伊都国|1=Itokoku|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Itokoku|13=User:Immanuelle/Itokoku|qq=}} * [[:en:Mikumo-Iwara_Site|Mikumo-Iwara Site]]
