== Overview == In February {{ill|1822|ja|文政5年|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1822|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, Seishiro Mitoma accidentally discovered the site while excavating soil from a field at Minamishouji for building walls<ref>{{Cite book|author=Itoshima District Social Education Promotion Council|title=Ito Kingdom Archaeological Guidebook|publisher=Itoshima Newspaper|date=2001-4-30|page=52}}</ref>. In [[:en:1974|Showa 49]][[Category:Years needing redirect replacements]], a re-excavation revealed the "second jar burial." Academic investigations during the Heisei period confirmed the presence of a surrounding moat, identifying the site as a "square-moat Kofun" containing two jar burials. The jars are classified as "Tateiwa-style early-phase" from the middle Yayoi period. Ritual traces have been observed in the western moat, with potential links to the {{ill|Mount Takasu|lt=Mount Takasu|lt=Takazusayama mountain range|ja|高祖山|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takazusayama mountain range|qq=}} to the east. These characteristics anticipate the features seen in the later {{ill|Hirabaru Ruins|ja|平原遺跡|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hirabaru Site|qq=|comment=enwiki is a redirect|comment=enwiki is a redirect}} Kofun 1<ref>"Mikumo Site: Minamishouji District," Fukuoka Prefectural Cultural Property Survey Report No. 69, Fukuoka Prefectural Board of Education, 1985.</ref>.
